{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T04:47:10.790Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "L1 and L2 regularization"}, {"type": "text", "text": " are two core techniques that prevent "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "overfitting"}, {"type": "text", "text": " in ML models by adding a "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "penalty term to the loss function"}, {"type": "text", "text": " that discourages large weights, thereby reducing model complexity and encouraging the model to focus on the overall structure of data rather than fitting noise."}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Simple definition:"}, {"type": "text", "text": " \"L1 and L2 regularization are methods used to mitigate overfitting in machine learning models. These techniques are often applied when a model's data set has a large number of features, and a less complex model is needed.\""}]}]}, {"type": "horizontalRule"}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "L1/L2 Regularization — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What overfitting is"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Overfitting"}, {"type": "text", "text": " happens when a model learns the training data "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "too well"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", including its noise and outliers, which hampers performance on new, unseen data:"}]}, {"type": "bulletList", "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Model has "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "low training error"}, {"type": "text", "text": " but "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"typ